      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/trajectory-inference-method-selection/003",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "In addition to implementing both Slingshot and Monocle 3 (refs. 41\u201343), two scRNA-seq trajectory algorithms, ArchR also provides its own supervised trajectory analysis. To do this analysis, ArchR initially creates a cellular trajectory based on the average positions (within a lower n-dimensional subspace) of a sequence of user-supplied clusters or groups.",
      "asbval:note": "Paper confirms Monocle 3 is implemented in ArchR and references reverse graph embedding (ref. 42: 'Reversed graph embedding resolves complex single-cell trajectories'), but the specific wrapper function name 'addMonocleTrajectory' is not explicitly stated in passages. The mechanism described (average positions, lower-dimensional subspace) describes ArchR's own supervised trajectory, not Monocle 3's specific algorithm.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1038-s41588-021-00790-6",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "partial",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "trajectory-inference-method-selection",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "tools",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "monocle3 - Trajectory inference engine invoked via ArchR's addMonocleTrajectory; computes pseudotime and cell-state transitions using graph-based reverse graph embedding",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000361"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T18:15:47.760356+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000339"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/trajectory-inference-method-selection/004",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "In addition to implementing both Slingshot and Monocle 3 (refs. 41\u201343), two scRNA-seq trajectory algorithms, ArchR also provides its own supervised trajectory analysis.",
      "asbval:note": "Paper confirms Slingshot is implemented in ArchR, but the specific wrapper function name 'addSlingShotTrajectories' is not explicitly stated in the provided passages. The cluster-based lineage inference is consistent with Slingshot's known approach but not explicitly described in these passages.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1038-s41588-021-00790-6",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "partial",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "trajectory-inference-method-selection",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "tools",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "Slingshot - Trajectory inference engine invoked via ArchR's addSlingShotTrajectories; computes cluster-based lineages and pseudotime on reduced-dimension embeddings",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000361"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T18:15:47.760356+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000339"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/trajectory-inference-method-selection/005",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "Here we present a software suite for single-cell analysis of regulatory chromatin in R (ArchR; https://www.archrproject.com/) that enables fast and comprehensive analysis of single-cell chromatin accessibility data.",
      "asbval:note": "ArchR is explicitly described as an R package, confirming R as the execution environment.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1038-s41588-021-00790-6",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "trajectory-inference-method-selection",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "tools",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "R - Execution language and environment for ArchR and all trajectory analysis functions",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T18:15:47.760356+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/trajectory-inference-method-selection/006",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "ArchR facilitates cellular trajectory analysis to identify the predicted path of gene regulatory changes from one set of cells to another, a unique type of insight enabled by single-cell data.",
      "asbval:note": "Paper confirms trajectory analysis is applied to scATAC-seq data in ArchR projects for discovering developmental/differentiation paths.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1038-s41588-021-00790-6",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "trajectory-inference-method-selection",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "scope",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "When you have an ArchR project object with processed single-cell ATAC-seq data and want to infer developmental or cell-state trajectories.",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T18:15:47.760356+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/trajectory-inference-method-selection/007",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "We benchmarked the performance of trajectory analysis in ArchR compared to those in Slingshot and Monocle 3 using a miniaturized version of the hematopoiesis dataset (n = 10,251) (Extended Data Fig. 10c). We compared the learned trajectories from stem and progenitor cells through differentiated B cells or monocytes and found that the inferred trajectories were highly similar (r2 > 0.96) (Extended Data Fig. 10d,e). The implementation of all three trajectory algorithms allows end users to select the implementation that best suits their analysis, as each trajectory method has distinct advantages.",
      "asbval:note": "Paper confirms user choice between methods and that each has distinct advantages, but does not explicitly characterize Monocle 3 as 'RNA velocity\u2013inspired' or Slingshot as 'clustering-based' in the provided passages. The characterization is conceptually consistent with known algorithm properties but not verbatim-confirmed.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1038-s41588-021-00790-6",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "partial",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "trajectory-inference-method-selection",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "scope",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "Use this skill when your analysis design requires choosing between Monocle3's RNA velocity\u2013inspired approach and Slingshot's clustering-based lineage inference",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000361"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T18:15:47.760356+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000339"
      }
    },
